9. Why This Works

The inserted character divides the optimal subsequence into:

matched characters before insertion,

the inserted character itself,

matched characters after insertion.


Since pre and suf already contain the best possible LCS values for the left and right parts, checking

pre + 1 + suf

exactly determines whether the insertion increases the LCS by one. Using a set ensures duplicate characters from s2 are counted only once per insertion position.


---

10. Edge Cases

Minimum length strings.

LCS already equals min(n1, n2).

Repeated characters in s2.

All characters different.

Insert at beginning.

Insert at end.

Empty prefix or suffix after insertion.



